        <body>       

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>From<lb/>
                Rev. Dr. Drachman<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Rockaway Beach Box 42</hi><lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais<lb/>
                546 N. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/>
                Pa.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rockaway Beach&#44; July 11&#47;88<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr.<lb/></p>
            <p>As you may need it for<lb/> the purpose of preparing a report<lb/> I again send a list of the subjects<lb/> in which the Seminary classes were<lb/> prepared for examination.  The<lb/> lower class had read with me&#44;<lb/> 20 chapters of Genesis with &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44;<lb/> 50 Psalms&#44; the history from Joshua<lb/> to the death of <hi rend="underline">David in the original</hi><lb/> and the Grammar of the Noun and<lb/> Verb.  The higher class read eight<lb/> &#40;not six&#41; chapters of Exodus with a<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>selection of commentators and in<lb/> Grammar had learnt the regular<lb/> verb.  With Dr. Lieberman the<lb/> lower class read Mishna Sabbath<lb/> and Talmud Bala Metzia and<lb/> the higher class Talmud Berachoth<lb/> and Chullin but the quantities I am<lb/> unable to state.<lb/></p>
            <p>There are two subjects on which I<lb/> am very anxious to be informed&#44;<lb/> firstly&#44; concerning the results of the<lb/> examination as affecting the arrang&#45;<lb/>&#45;ement of classes it being evident<lb/> that the lower class contains boys of very<lb/> different degrees of progress&#44; secondly&#44;<lb/> concerning the <del>&#91;&#63;&#93;</del> course of<lb/> studies for the next years as I do<lb/> not how we are to arrange it in<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>order to make it correspond to the de&#45;<lb/>&#45;mands of the curriculum.  Perhaps<lb/> when you are again in New York you<lb/> will arrange for a conference to settle<lb/> this point.  I delivered my first<lb/> lecture of the summer course last Sun&#45;<lb/>&#45;day&#44; the Seminarists were all<lb/> present but very few of the general<lb/> public.  I have also called on the<lb/> Chief Rabbi of the Polish congregation&#44;<lb/> who impressed me very favorably.<lb/>  At my next visit I shall try to<lb/> bring up the matter of the Seminary<lb/> and gain him over.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping to have the pleasure of meeting<lb/> you soon again&#44; I remain<lb/> very respectfully<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            </body>
